(II) Has Traditional Chinese Opera Really Declined?

Decline in Operatic Genres and Shrinking Performance Ranges for Local Operas
According to reports from Xinhua Net, there were 368 local opera genres nationwide in 1959, which peaked at 374 in 1983, but plummeted to just 286 by 2012. Starting in July 2015, the Ministry of Culture launched a two-year nationwide comprehensive census of local opera genres. The statistical results revealed a total of 348 local opera genres across China.

[T1: Bar Chart of Fluctuations in Opera Genre Quantities (Featuring rising Q-version characters)]

Among them, 300 genres are confined to only one single province, municipality, or autonomous region. Only 48 genres span across two or more provinces, illustrating the highly restricted geographic mobility of local opera types.

There are 17 genres that were omitted from the Chronicles of Chinese Opera but were supplemented into this census directory, falling into four distinct categories:

Genres that were once popular, subsequently declined, and have now been restored (1 genre): Hamaweng (Toad Drone).

Independent genres that split from original genres due to variations in geographic region or musical structure (4 genres): Huaian Ruanyangge, Xianziciang, Shadong Luozi, and Denqiang.

Hidden genres that were undiscovered or overlooked when editing the Chronicles of Chinese Opera (8 genres): Wuan Nuo Opera, Zhegu Opera, Ai Opera, Mulao Opera, Guoluo Mounted Tibetan Opera, Yushu Gesar Tibetan Opera, Bagong Opera, and Sherpa Mani Opera.

Genres evolved from folk vocal arts or fused from multiple minor operatic plays (4 genres): Yunju Opera, Manhan Opera, Ziyang Folk Song Opera, and Stilt Bamboo Horse Opera.

