Conversely, 60 genres that were originally recorded in the Chronicles of Chinese Opera were completely absent from this recent census directory, categorizable into three types:

The First Type: Genres that had already vanished decades before the Chronicles of Chinese Opera was compiled in the 1980s and 1990s but were included for historical context (19 genres): Huaihong Opera, Dingding Qiang, Tianjin Vocal Art Opera, Wenming (Civilized) Opera, Southern Opera, Shandong Luantan, Zhuchun, Qing Opera, Kunyi, Manchu Bajiaogu Opera, Jing Qiang, Shaanxi Sai Opera, Xifu Qinqiang, Southern Fujian Siping Opera, Dui Opera, Ruicheng Lahu Opera, Yanbei Xianziqiang, Wanrong Qing Opera, and Yicheng Mulian Opera. These genres had already been extinct for decades when the chronicles were written, and their entries served merely to illustrate the historical evolution of the respective provinces.

The reasons for their extinction vary. Due to administrative policies, Xuzhou's Dingding Qiang collapsed because the rural household registration (hukou) of its veteran artists could not be transferred into the city, forcing the opera school to painfully dissolve the "Xuju Opera" class. Elsewhere, due to misdirected values, the late-stage Civilized Opera of Tianjin focused strictly on displaying domestic ugliness and playing up scandalous affairs (such as The She-Tiger and Strife Between Wives and Concubines), completely alienating the audience and driving the art form down a path of self-destruction.

The Second Type: Genres with zero performance troupes, zero active artists (or just isolated individuals), no structural inheritance, and absolutely no performance activities (24 genres): Gaochun Yangqiang Mulian Opera, Xiaoluozi, Pengbandiao, Erhulu, Nancindiao, Yujiale (Fisherman's Joy), Uyghur Opera, Jian Opera, Ruihe Opera, Fuhe Opera, Jingdezhen Tea-Picking Opera, Lingao Human-Puppet Opera, Guizhou Bangzi, Guyuan Quzi, Longde Quzi, Zhongwei Yangge, Yanchi Quzi, Yinchuan Quzi, Anhui Duangong Opera, Sichuan Tu Opera, Yicheng Yangge, Pinglu Flower-Drum Opera, Xiaxian Xianer Opera, and Xiaxian Hamaweng.

The Third Type: Genres with zero performance troupes but a handful of surviving master artists, active inheritance channels, and occasional performance footprints, making them not yet fully extinct (17 genres): Hudiao, Ruihe Tea-Picking Opera, Guer Opera, Western Guangdong Bai Opera, Hailufeng Bamboo Horse Opera, Luozi Opera, Songyang Gaoqiang, Xinggan Opera, Zhuji Luantan, Zhejiang Mulian Opera, Zhejiang Nuo Opera, Ciming Opera, Zezhou Yangge, Jiexiu Gandiao Yangge, Huanghua Fishing-Drum Opera, West Route Pingju Opera, and Linyuan Shadow-Tone Opera.

