Troupes and Ensembles Are Predominantly Privately Managed; Growth of Opera-Related Enterprises Slows Down
(1) Grassroots Private Troupes Shoulder the Heavy Burden of Cultural Inheritance

In 2004, there were 1,544 opera troupes nationwide, accounting for 56% of the national total of performing arts groups.

In 2010, the number reached 2,451 troupes (35.7% of the total), remaining the largest category of performing arts organizations in the country.

By 2017, the total number of theatrical opera troupes expanded to 10,278, among which 8,754 were private ensembles (including grassroots folk troupes)—a volume 5.7 times greater than state-owned institutions. Among the 348 recorded genres, 44.40% have no state-run troupes at all, and 70 genres rely entirely on grassroots folk troupes. The survival of these genres is highly precarious, facing the constant threat of "troupe dissolution leading to genre extinction."

