Relatively Lower Average Ticket Prices and Overall Box Office Returns

The market prospects for the traditional live opera performance industry remain worrisome.

Looking vertically, although the total number of opera performance sessions in 2021 surpassed pre-pandemic 2019 levels, box office revenues only recovered to 90% of 2019. By 2022, total opera box office revenue fell sharply to 208 million RMB—a staggering 87.00% decrease, making the annual total less than the box office of just the third quarter of 2019. In 2022, the average ticket price for traditional opera continued its downward trend to 92 RMB, a drop of 17.86% compared to the previous year. Throughout the year, performances in novel performance settings such as small theaters accounted for 73.06% of all sessions.

Looking horizontally, traditional opera staged 17,900 performances in 2021—outnumbering stage plays, musicals, and children's plays. However, its box office generated a mere 769 million RMB, lagging far behind alternative performing art forms. This discrepancy is driven by ticket pricing: the average ticket price for an opera was 112 RMB, whereas dance, stage plays, and musicals all broke the 200 RMB threshold. By 2022, while the average opera ticket slipped further to 92 RMB, dance, stage plays, and musicals saw their average ticket prices surge past 400 RMB.

