In the current market, talk shows and immersive theater experiences enjoy immense popularity. Yu Qingfeng, a famous playwright from Zhejiang and a three-time winner of the "Cao Yu Script Award," points out that the ancestors of these modern formats are actually traditional Chinese operas. For example, techniques like improvisational bantering (Chake Dahun) and introducing oneself directly to the audience (Zibao Jiamen) are inherent characteristics of classical opera. Similarly, the Nuo Opera of Guizhou was inherently an immersive performance involving the entire village. Historically, opera was the largest cultural industry in China. Yu Qingfeng believes there is only one way to make opera glorious again: creating market value for it. This means playwrights must craft repertoires that everyday citizens genuinely want to see; only then can the industry achieve sustainable growth.

