The deeply regional nature of local opera inherently limits its audience reach. According to 2021 data from Damai, over 60% of ticket buyers for pop concerts, music festivals, and trendy commercial theater shows were willing to travel cross-city to watch a show. Even in 2022, when large-scale concerts and music festivals drastically decreased, 32% of consumers still opted for cross-city travel to watch performances. Hit stage plays, talk shows, small theater productions, and indie singer concerts in live houses became the preferred choices for cross-city consumers in 2022.

Support and Institutional Policies
Traditional opera is a treasure of Chinese culture, forming an essential component of outstanding traditional culture and serving as an effective vehicle for deepening international exchange and demonstrating national cultural soft power. The Ministry of Culture and Tourism attaches great importance to the inheritance and development of opera. In recent years, focusing on operatic creation and overseas dissemination, it has primarily carried out the following initiatives:

First, stimulating and guiding artistic creation by building showcase platforms and executing structural creative projects. It has continuously hosted premium festivals such as the China Art Festival, China Peking Opera Art Festival, China Kunqu Opera Art Festival, China Yue Opera Art Festival, China (Anqing) Huangmei Opera Art Festival, and the Opera Hundred戏 (Kunshan) Extravaganza. It also spearheads showcase events like the National Grassroots Troupe Opera Festival, the National Local Opera Southern (Northern) Showcase, the China Qinqiang Outstanding Repertoire Exhibition, and the National Caichaxi (Tea-Picking Opera) Gathering, incentivizing troupes at all levels to forge masterpieces.

Second, supporting the inheritance and staging of traditional classics and milestone repertoires. Under the guidance of the Central Publicity Department, the Ministry launched the "Chinese Peking Opera Digital Audio-Visual Project (Xiang-Yin-Xiang)" in 2016, carefully capturing and recording iconic actors and repertoires from key troupes to preserve the masteries of contemporary Peking Opera icons. In 2020, the Central Publicity Department and the Ministry of Culture and Tourism jointly initiated the broader "Chinese Traditional Opera Digital Audio-Visual Project," mapping out a blueprint to record 500 classical works, with 73 works completely finalized to date.

Third, innovating communication channels by leveraging new media networks like "文艺中国 (Cultural China)" and "中国艺术头条 (China Art Headlines)" to market key performances, outstanding troupes, and premier works. Maintaining a dual focus on internal and external dissemination, the Ministry has long built pipelines for the overseas expansion and touring of Chinese opera troupes.

Fifth, reinforcing financial support. The government has systematically coordinated funds to finance free or low-cost ticket performances of endangered opera genres, the "Opera into Campuses" initiative, national local opera censuses, master-to-disciple transmission projects, and grassroots troupe showcase exhibitions. The funds are primarily channeled into opera creation, production, communication, marketing, archival collection, and talent incubation. Outstanding talents can compete in prestigious competitions like the Plum Performance Award, the Wenhua Award, and the Cao Yu Script Award.

In 2019, the central government allocated 389 million RMB to deliver approximately 80,000 public welfare performances, focused primarily on local opera, across 12,984 impoverished rural townships.

Launched in 2021, the Ministry of Culture and Tourism continuously runs the "Endangered Genre Free or Low-Cost Performance Project," enabling local governments to purchase services. This project funds public-welfare performances across 227 genres that possess either zero or exactly one state-run troupe, utilizing live performance as the core driver for endangered genre rescue. Each genre is allocated an average purchase of 100 performances annually (with traditional classics accounting for no less than 80% of the repertoire), offering an average subsidy of 5,000 RMB per performance session.

In 2022, the Ministry of Finance distributed central government subsidies for local public cultural service system construction, allocating a total of 1.232 billion RMB. The guidelines explicitly specified that standard public-welfare opera performances are calculated at a baseline of delivering 6 shows per township annually, subsidized at 5,000 RMB per show. Specialized public-welfare opera performances (focusing on endangered genres) are funded based on the exact quantity of endangered genres and specific metrics (purchasing 100 performances per year at 5,000 RMB per session) to determine provincial allocations.

Sixth, persistently cultivating troupe talent while strengthening professional opera vocational education. In terms of institutional talent, the goal is to roll out elite practitioners across multiple disciplines to drive a harmonized development across creation, performance, and critique. From 2016 onward, the Ministry held advanced seminars for opera talent cultivation for 5 consecutive years, training nearly 1,000 professional playwrights, directors, composers, stage designers, and critics. The "Master Passing Down Art — Contemporary Opera Master Apprentice Engineering" has directly benefited over 1,000 young performers.

Looking at the data, the state has maintained consistent attention and poured structural funding into protecting and sustaining traditional opera. However, as Zhang Junbo’s story reveals like a microcosm, a massive portion of exceptional grassroots actors still struggle to secure basic livelihood guarantees, leaving their artistic passions unfulfilled. The institutional support for traditional opera must be further routed into practical grassroots enforcement, precisely targeting the actual funding gaps. (Note: This support policy block can be further condensed if necessary)

(IV) The Future: "Internet + Traditional Opera"

It must be admitted that the decline of traditional Chinese opera is not a baseless rumor; intricate vocal melodies and flowing silk sleeves have gradually lost their grip on modern society, falling into the dilemma of being "highly praised but poorly attended."

Yet beneath the seemingly still waters, a vibrant new current is surging. On new media channels like Douyin and Bilibili, opera livestreaming rooms and performance videos are pulling in a massive wave of new fans, transforming virtual livestreaming tips into "the new theater tickets." Although deep issues like outdated content structures and actor career bottlenecks remain unresolved, traditional opera has caught a brilliant ray of dawn on the "Cloud Stage" amid the concrete jungles of high-rises.

Diminishing Appeal of Traditional Media Channels
As offline performance spaces face bleak prospects, traditional opera—as a cultural product and symbolic icon—must lean on media ecosystems to amplify its dissemination, influence, and competitiveness.

However, turning our gaze to legacy media, the viewership data for television opera programming is equally discouraging. Taking the opera segments on the CCTV Spring Festival Gala as an example: in 1985, opera performances accounted for a solid 15.7% of the entire broadcast runtime. Since then, it has steadily dwindled, hitting a low of 1.5% in 2013, and crawling back to a mere 4.3% by 2022.

