(3) A Fresh Arena for Grassroots Performers
In April 2022, Douyin Live rolled out the "DOU Has Good Opera" initiative, pledging to help at least 10 institutional troupes and 1,000 professional actors construct an online "Second Stage" within a year. At a recent event, Douyin disclosed the latest milestones: as of this April, 2,705 professional opera actors and 163 institutional troupes have successfully integrated into the program, utilizing live streams to stage online performances.

By adopting opera streaming as a viable side-hustle, grassroots actors are successfully subsidizing their institutional income. Chen Yu, a Yue Opera performer from Xiangshan, Ningbo, Zhejiang, observed: "Among the private folk opera performers I know, roughly two-fifths are now actively streaming on Douyin."

Inside the streaming room of Yu Opera host Di Xueli, the clock ticks past 11:00 PM, yet over 1,000 viewers remain glued to the screen. During a live-stream battle (PK challenge), several opera hosts take turns belting out snippets of various local genres. In the end, Di Xueli clinches the victory. She smoothly thanks her gifting fans in her local dialect. In the final seconds of the PK round, she rakes in two virtual "Hot Air Balloons" and a "Porsche"—totaling roughly 320 RMB in real-world currency—and this represents merely a tiny fraction of her earnings for the night.

Her triumph is far from an isolated case. Dai Hongbo, head of Douyin Live’s opera vertical operations, stated that between May and December 2022, Douyin supported a total of 1,054 professional opera actors, boosting their livestream revenues by 86% month-on-month, while also onboarding 124 institutional troupes for digital streaming. Since 2022, the aggregate streaming revenue of opera hosts shot up by 81.36% year-on-year, with hosts hailing from Zhejiang enjoying an impressive 99.64% surge. Broken down by specific genres, the absolute highest-grossing genre in Shanghai and Zhejiang is Yue Opera, while Jiangsu's top earner is Huaiju Opera.

